00:00:47.220 --> 00:00:50.000
And so that already
is part of the success

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:53.334
story about how technology is
beginning to change government.

00:00:53.334 --> 00:00:55.250
So this is, of course--
this is not of course.

00:00:55.250 --> 00:00:59.720
This is a picture from one
of my favorite restaurants

00:00:59.720 --> 00:01:00.295
in Chicago.

00:01:00.295 --> 00:01:02.420
This is probably better
known to you than data.gov.

00:01:02.420 --> 00:01:03.510
It's called Alinea.

00:01:03.510 --> 00:01:05.746
Its the top rated
restaurant in Chicago.

00:01:05.746 --> 00:01:07.120
And the reason I
show this to you

00:01:07.120 --> 00:01:11.440
is not only because I love
food, but because Chicago

00:01:11.440 --> 00:01:13.600
is one of those places
that has a great success

00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:15.050
story around open data, right?

00:01:15.050 --> 00:01:20.820
Typically the way a city
deals with food borne illness

00:01:20.820 --> 00:01:24.370
is through sending out a couple
of inspectors into restaurants.

00:01:24.370 --> 00:01:26.100
They go down a
list, you know, go

00:01:26.100 --> 00:01:28.860
through the list of the whole
restaurants once a year, right?

00:01:28.860 --> 00:01:30.360
And they inspect
them one at a time.

00:01:30.360 --> 00:01:31.700
So what does Chicago do, right?

00:01:31.700 --> 00:01:33.910
They look at the data,
the open data that

00:01:33.910 --> 00:01:36.560
now exists about the
incidence of food

00:01:36.560 --> 00:01:38.300
borne illness and restaurants.

00:01:38.300 --> 00:01:40.750
And they develop an
algorithm to prioritize which

00:01:40.750 --> 00:01:42.510
restaurants to inspect first.

00:01:42.510 --> 00:01:45.170
Because Chicago, like London,
being a great food town,

00:01:45.170 --> 00:01:47.410
of course, has
thousands of restaurants

00:01:47.410 --> 00:01:51.140
but only a handful of inspectors
to have to do this major job.

00:01:51.140 --> 00:01:53.130
And so they've been able
to dramatically reduce

00:01:53.130 --> 00:01:57.020
the incidence of illness,
serious and otherwise,

00:01:57.020 --> 00:02:00.420
by using data to improve
how government functions.

00:02:00.420 --> 00:02:03.270
So this is just but one example
of some of the successes

00:02:03.270 --> 00:02:06.330
that we've seen since Obama
on his first day in office,

00:02:06.330 --> 00:02:09.522
and Cameron not too long
after his first day in office,

00:02:09.522 --> 00:02:11.730
said, we're going to turn
around and open up the data

00:02:11.730 --> 00:02:13.160
that government holds.

00:02:13.160 --> 00:02:15.300
This was part of a
three-prong strategy

00:02:15.300 --> 00:02:17.380
to change fundamentally
how government

00:02:17.380 --> 00:02:19.014
works using technology, right?

00:02:19.014 --> 00:02:20.680
We're going to make
it more transparent.

00:02:20.680 --> 00:02:22.730
We're going to make
it more participatory.

00:02:22.730 --> 00:02:24.680
And we're going to make
it more collaborative.

00:02:24.680 --> 00:02:27.590
And that open data story
has led to a lot of success

00:02:27.590 --> 00:02:28.750
and a lot of impacts.

00:02:28.750 --> 00:02:30.390
We're just, of course,
at the beginning

00:02:30.390 --> 00:02:32.640
of that revolution
in data driven

00:02:32.640 --> 00:02:35.320
government and governing.

00:02:35.320 --> 00:02:37.630
But we're seeing a lot of
ways in which data is helping

00:02:37.630 --> 00:02:39.220
government to work
better, to become

00:02:39.220 --> 00:02:42.760
more accountable, enabling
more businesses to get started.

00:02:42.760 --> 00:02:44.660
Google uses a lot
of open government

00:02:44.660 --> 00:02:47.500
data in its own businesses
to drive a lot of services

00:02:47.500 --> 00:02:49.340
that you provide to consumers.

00:02:49.340 --> 00:02:51.152
It enables consumers,
of course, thanks

00:02:51.152 --> 00:02:52.610
to some of the
innovations that you

00:02:52.610 --> 00:02:55.840
create, to make better choices
like which hospital to go

00:02:55.840 --> 00:02:58.050
to based on the
comparative infection

00:02:58.050 --> 00:03:00.160
rates at those hospitals--
again, something

00:03:00.160 --> 00:03:03.070
I can get from looking on Google
but that's driven ultimately

00:03:03.070 --> 00:03:04.840
by government data.

00:03:04.840 --> 00:03:07.340
But the lesser
developed story is

00:03:07.340 --> 00:03:10.550
what's happening in those other
two areas of participation

00:03:10.550 --> 00:03:11.780
and collaboration.

00:03:11.780 --> 00:03:13.530
So if the last five
years has really

00:03:13.530 --> 00:03:15.740
have been about
beginning the revolution

00:03:15.740 --> 00:03:19.280
in open data, the next five
years, I want to put to you,

00:03:19.280 --> 00:03:23.270
is going to be about that shift
from data.gov to people.gov,

00:03:23.270 --> 00:03:26.220
to using technology,
data driven technologies,

00:03:26.220 --> 00:03:29.030
to enable us to do
for our country,

00:03:29.030 --> 00:03:32.060
to participate in new ways, to
make our government smarter,

00:03:32.060 --> 00:03:33.400
and to make it more effective.

00:03:33.400 --> 00:03:36.600
And we can see whether
I can convince Will

00:03:36.600 --> 00:03:38.220
that we can actually
do things better

00:03:38.220 --> 00:03:39.930
than we can do them today.

00:03:39.930 --> 00:03:41.900
And let me say as a
caveat in the outset,

00:03:41.900 --> 00:03:43.930
and though I'm happy
to talk in the Q&amp;A

00:03:43.930 --> 00:03:47.940
about politics--
coming from the US,

00:03:47.940 --> 00:03:50.660
there's plenty to
talk about right now.

00:03:50.660 --> 00:03:52.530
But what I'm talking
to you about today

00:03:52.530 --> 00:03:54.800
is what happens the
day after the election.

00:03:54.800 --> 00:03:57.190
So after Bernie Sanders,
or Donald Trump,

00:03:57.190 --> 00:04:00.960
or whoever it may be becomes
president in November,

00:04:00.960 --> 00:04:04.040
and after you exit Europe,
or you don't exit Europe,

00:04:04.040 --> 00:04:06.040
and Scotland leaves, or
it doesn't, or whatever

00:04:06.040 --> 00:04:07.827
is going to happen
in the next year,

00:04:07.827 --> 00:04:09.410
it has to do with
what happens the day

00:04:09.410 --> 00:04:11.200
after these political
decisions are

00:04:11.200 --> 00:04:14.350
made that allow us to deliver
health care, and education,

00:04:14.350 --> 00:04:17.910
and take out the trash, and
solve problems of illness,

00:04:17.910 --> 00:04:20.709
and pandemic, and global
warming, et cetera.

00:04:20.709 --> 00:04:23.020
So technology is
beginning to help us to do

00:04:23.020 --> 00:04:24.330
these things better, right?

00:04:24.330 --> 00:04:27.640
We have for a long
time held the ideal

00:04:27.640 --> 00:04:31.500
and known about the idea of
asking citizens for their input

00:04:31.500 --> 00:04:34.490
into how we make decisions,
usually by asking people

00:04:34.490 --> 00:04:36.050
for their opinion, right?

00:04:36.050 --> 00:04:36.794
We poll people.

00:04:36.794 --> 00:04:38.460
Well, how do you feel
about this policy?

00:04:38.460 --> 00:04:40.140
Should we exit Europe or not?

00:04:40.140 --> 00:04:41.690
Should Scotland leave or not?

00:04:41.690 --> 00:04:45.030
And technology is helping us to
do that faster and more quickly

00:04:45.030 --> 00:04:46.590
than we've done it before.

00:04:46.590 --> 00:04:48.460
How many people
have actually signed

00:04:48.460 --> 00:04:50.880
a petition on E-petitions?

00:04:50.880 --> 00:04:52.480
Oh, quite a number.

00:04:52.480 --> 00:04:55.580
How many people have written
a petition, posted a petition?

00:04:55.580 --> 00:04:58.780
Any disgruntled folk out
there-- on either this site

00:04:58.780 --> 00:04:59.535
or this site?

00:05:00.520 --> 00:05:01.680
Let me see the hand.

00:05:01.680 --> 00:05:04.430
What was the petition
that you signed,

00:05:04.430 --> 00:05:06.622
for someone who signed one?

00:05:06.622 --> 00:05:08.080
There was a lot of
hands that went.

00:05:08.080 --> 00:05:08.880
I think there was one--

00:05:08.880 --> 00:05:09.090
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:09.090 --> 00:05:10.150
Nobody's willing, sorry.

00:05:10.150 --> 00:05:12.170
I don't want to, you
know-- you're in the US,

00:05:12.170 --> 00:05:14.160
of course, the two
most popular petitions,

00:05:14.160 --> 00:05:16.650
you know what they were.

00:05:16.650 --> 00:05:18.940
So the two most popular
petitions, yes, you know.

