[LAUGHTER]

00:05:31.370 --> 00:05:33.580
Very apropos with the
Grammy's this week.

00:05:33.580 --> 00:05:36.300
So I'm not sure I've
convinced Will yet.

00:05:36.300 --> 00:05:38.180
If I stop here, I
haven't convinced will

00:05:38.180 --> 00:05:40.180
that we're making
government work any better

00:05:40.180 --> 00:05:44.170
using technology if that's
the best that we can do.

00:05:44.170 --> 00:05:46.420
What's interesting though
is the ways in which,

00:05:46.420 --> 00:05:48.130
perhaps a little
less well known,

00:05:48.130 --> 00:05:49.930
that we're beginning
to use technology

00:05:49.930 --> 00:05:53.940
to actually get at not what
people feel about politics,

00:05:53.940 --> 00:05:57.680
and policy, and government,
but that actually get

00:05:57.680 --> 00:05:59.380
at what people know and can do.

00:05:59.380 --> 00:06:01.770
So we're seeing lots of
instances of the ways

00:06:01.770 --> 00:06:06.840
in which NGOs more so,
but government beginning,

00:06:06.840 --> 00:06:09.260
are tapping into
what people can do.

00:06:09.260 --> 00:06:10.720
I don't have a
slide up for it now.

00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:12.520
But for this room,
I want to make

00:06:12.520 --> 00:06:15.160
sure to point out to you that in
British Columbia, for example,

00:06:15.160 --> 00:06:17.330
they've created something
called the BC Developers

00:06:17.330 --> 00:06:20.110
Exchange, which is a way that
the government is reaching out

00:06:20.110 --> 00:06:21.950
to engineers and
techies in the community

00:06:21.950 --> 00:06:23.980
to get help with doing
technical projects

00:06:23.980 --> 00:06:25.430
and lending their know-how.

00:06:25.430 --> 00:06:28.120
In Sao Paulo, starting in
November, Brazil's largest

00:06:28.120 --> 00:06:30.600
city, the government
said, we don't know enough

00:06:30.600 --> 00:06:32.070
about tech and innovation.

00:06:32.070 --> 00:06:33.840
And so instead of
our usual method

00:06:33.840 --> 00:06:37.480
of sending civil servants to the
civil service training college,

00:06:37.480 --> 00:06:39.960
we're going to ask people in
the community to teach us.

00:06:39.960 --> 00:06:42.376
We're going to come to you and
say, want to teach courses?

00:06:42.376 --> 00:06:45.120
Want to teach
government how to use R,

00:06:45.120 --> 00:06:49.280
how to use Python, how to
scrape data, how to whatever

00:06:49.280 --> 00:06:50.040
it may be?

00:06:50.040 --> 00:06:50.950
You pick the topic.

00:06:50.950 --> 00:06:52.283
You tell us what we should know.

00:06:52.283 --> 00:06:54.310
And now they have 24,000
government officials

00:06:54.310 --> 00:06:57.460
enrolled in courses
taught by techie citizens

00:06:57.460 --> 00:07:00.140
to teach them to become
more tech literate.

00:07:00.140 --> 00:07:02.490
A lot of these projects
are also not just

00:07:02.490 --> 00:07:06.190
about kind of time and tasks,
but also about ideas, right?

00:07:06.190 --> 00:07:09.980
So if I go on Madrid
website right now,

00:07:09.980 --> 00:07:12.640
I can share my know-how
about how to create

00:07:12.640 --> 00:07:14.770
Madrid's new transparency law.

00:07:14.770 --> 00:07:17.220
I can go to Paris
and tell the mayor

00:07:17.220 --> 00:07:19.150
where to put more
bathrooms in Paris

00:07:19.150 --> 00:07:21.560
or what I think we
should do better there.

00:07:21.560 --> 00:07:27.620
And we can contribute our
know-how as well as our views

00:07:27.620 --> 00:07:28.340
about things.

00:07:28.340 --> 00:07:31.120
So I got my start in
doing a lot of this work,

00:07:31.120 --> 00:07:33.664
or the best known
project I've done,

00:07:33.664 --> 00:07:36.080
before going to the White
House, was a project called Peer

00:07:36.080 --> 00:07:37.090
to Patent.

00:07:37.090 --> 00:07:40.890
It was designed to enable
volunteer technologists

00:07:40.890 --> 00:07:46.480
and scientists out there in
industry and in universities

00:07:46.480 --> 00:07:48.850
to volunteer 10
minutes of their time

00:07:48.850 --> 00:07:52.780
to share advice and information
with a patent examiner.

00:07:52.780 --> 00:07:55.030
Because a patent examiner,
at least in those days,

00:07:55.030 --> 00:07:58.030
had about 15 hours to
do all the research

00:07:58.030 --> 00:08:01.360
and do all the work of
examining the patents that

00:08:01.360 --> 00:08:03.160
would get the next,
you know, 20 years

00:08:03.160 --> 00:08:05.830
of monopoly rights over
the technology that goes

00:08:05.830 --> 00:08:07.479
into this phone, for example.

00:08:07.479 --> 00:08:09.520
Sorry, I'm not allowed to
show this phone, right?

00:08:09.520 --> 00:08:14.240
That other phone-- wee, that's
why they're in lawsuits, right?

00:08:14.240 --> 00:08:16.260
Because you only have
15 hours to do the work.

00:08:16.260 --> 00:08:19.420
So why not reach out to the
people in this room and say,

00:08:19.420 --> 00:08:21.510
who knows about this issue?

00:08:21.510 --> 00:08:23.760
For the patent examiner,
it takes 15 hours.

00:08:23.760 --> 00:08:25.750
For you, it probably
would take 15 minutes,

00:08:25.750 --> 00:08:28.680
because it's the thing you
work on in your day job.

00:08:28.680 --> 00:08:31.030
So fast forward
to five years ago,

00:08:31.030 --> 00:08:34.370
2011, and the federal
government in the United States

00:08:34.370 --> 00:08:38.401
builds on this idea to create
a website called challenge.gov.

00:08:38.401 --> 00:08:40.085
So I've tested you
on the data.gov.

00:08:40.085 --> 00:08:45.830
How many people have been on
or participated in a Challenge?

00:08:45.830 --> 00:08:48.280
Whoa, for the record, no hands.

00:08:48.280 --> 00:08:48.920
Am I correct?

00:08:48.920 --> 00:08:51.790
Not a single hand.

00:08:51.790 --> 00:08:53.730
So I would encourage
you to go on here.

00:08:53.730 --> 00:08:56.260
They pay you enough at
Google, so you may not

00:08:56.260 --> 00:08:58.710
need to win the multimillion
dollar prizes that

00:08:58.710 --> 00:09:02.220
are on here for coming up
with an idea for how to remove

00:09:02.220 --> 00:09:05.600
the salt from salt water
to improve agriculture

00:09:05.600 --> 00:09:08.010
and farming in the
developing world.

00:09:08.010 --> 00:09:10.970
You don't necessarily need
to earn the prize that

00:09:10.970 --> 00:09:13.830
relates to how to use
technology to reduce the word

00:09:13.830 --> 00:09:17.120
gap between the number of words
a rich child and a poor child

00:09:17.120 --> 00:09:19.860
hears before he or
she is five years old.

00:09:19.860 --> 00:09:21.180
But you could.

00:09:21.180 --> 00:09:23.180
And it's a little
depressing that you don't

00:09:23.180 --> 00:09:25.310
know about that opportunity.

00:09:25.310 --> 00:09:27.890
Maybe food is your
thing, as it is for me.

00:09:27.890 --> 00:09:31.000
You want to help the European
Food Safety Agency, which

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:36.947
after the controversy over
its rulings on GMO cereals--

00:09:36.947 --> 00:09:39.280
in other words, saying they're
safe when a lot of people

00:09:39.280 --> 00:09:41.040
feel that they're
not-- they're now

00:09:41.040 --> 00:09:43.980
moving to look at how they can
crowdsource expertise instead

00:09:43.980 --> 00:09:46.180
of making these
scientific decisions,

00:09:46.180 --> 00:09:49.750
controversial scientific
decisions behind closed doors.

00:09:49.750 --> 00:09:51.630
The challenge and
the problem, though,

00:09:51.630 --> 00:09:53.880
that I would put
to you, the reason

00:09:53.880 --> 00:09:57.550
that you haven't been on
challenge.gov and the reason

00:09:57.550 --> 00:10:00.770
that government doesn't look
fundamentally different today

00:10:00.770 --> 00:10:03.900
than it did 10 years
ago is a problem

00:10:03.900 --> 00:10:06.070
that technology can
help us to solve.

00:10:06.070 --> 00:10:09.000
And that is that the way
that we do participation,

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:12.300
the way that we do engagement,
co-creation, co-production,

00:10:12.300 --> 00:10:15.850
whatever you want to call it is
through the open call, right?

00:10:15.850 --> 00:10:18.320
Challenge.gov is,
hey, anyone out there

00:10:18.320 --> 00:10:21.980
who has a good idea for removing
the salt from salt water

00:10:21.980 --> 00:10:23.524
to improve farming?

00:10:23.524 --> 00:10:24.690
And you don't know about it.

00:10:24.690 --> 00:10:27.520
It's a tree falling in a forest,
because the government is

00:10:27.520 --> 00:10:29.470
terrible at marketing, right?

00:10:29.470 --> 00:10:31.190
It's terrible it's sales.

00:10:31.190 --> 00:10:33.910
It is not very good at
doing what companies

00:10:33.910 --> 00:10:36.870
know how to do so well, which
is to segment their audiences

00:10:36.870 --> 00:10:38.160
and customers, right?

00:10:38.160 --> 00:10:42.600
You know exactly when to
give me an ad for whatever it

00:10:42.600 --> 00:10:44.090
is that you're
giving me an ad for.

00:10:44.090 --> 00:10:46.600
Somebody, whoever out there is
responsible for all those ads

00:10:46.600 --> 00:10:49.309
that I have to read, you give
me the ads that I want to read,

00:10:49.309 --> 00:10:50.850
because you know
what I'm looking at.

00:10:50.850 --> 00:10:54.570
And you know also that
because of my behavior

00:10:54.570 --> 00:10:57.740
and my characteristics, I am
more likely to buy toothpaste

00:10:57.740 --> 00:10:59.680
in the afternoon that
I am in the morning.

00:10:59.680 --> 00:11:02.940
And you know that with
some scientific precision--

00:11:02.940 --> 00:11:06.540
a very well-developed trend
in companies, not something

00:11:06.540 --> 00:11:08.030
we do well within government.

00:11:08.030 --> 00:11:11.490
Now I'm not talking about
heavy levels of data

00:11:11.490 --> 00:11:12.890
driven surveillance here.

00:11:12.890 --> 00:11:16.760
I'm talking about doing some
very lightweight curation

00:11:16.760 --> 00:11:19.840
of the audiences who are out
there and better apprising them

00:11:19.840 --> 00:11:21.940
of opportunities to participate.

00:11:21.940 --> 00:11:24.740
Because right now it's too hard
to find the people who know.

00:11:24.740 --> 00:11:28.440
It's too hard to connect
you to challenge.gov.

00:11:28.440 --> 00:11:30.530
It's also very hard,
and we're not used to,

00:11:30.530 --> 00:11:32.400
and we don't have the
cultural experience

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:35.660
that you know so well from going
on Stack Exchange and saying,

00:11:35.660 --> 00:11:38.280
hey, anybody out there have
the answer to what line of code

00:11:38.280 --> 00:11:39.860
is going to make my program run?

00:11:39.860 --> 00:11:42.240
We don't know well how
to do that in government.

00:11:42.240 --> 00:11:44.590
Because of course,
we have a tradition

00:11:44.590 --> 00:11:47.690
and a culture of governing
behind closed doors.

00:11:47.690 --> 00:11:51.400
If I say, in government, I
don't know, and I'm ignorant,

00:11:51.400 --> 00:11:54.830
I'm in the Daily Mail tomorrow,
right-- as the ignorant person

00:11:54.830 --> 00:11:56.050
who doesn't know.

00:11:56.050 --> 00:11:58.730
But also, it's very hard
to formulate a question.

00:11:58.730 --> 00:12:01.610
On Stack Exchange, it's
very easy to say, you know,

00:12:01.610 --> 00:12:04.290
what is the particular
aperture for my camera

00:12:04.290 --> 00:12:07.040
that I should use when
taking this picture?

00:12:07.040 --> 00:12:08.910
But that's not
the same thing as,

00:12:08.910 --> 00:12:11.950
how do I reduce the backlog
in veterans benefits claims?

00:12:11.950 --> 00:12:14.720
How do I improve health
care, cure cancer?

00:12:14.720 --> 00:12:16.830
The questions that
government tends to work on

00:12:16.830 --> 00:12:19.710
do not lend themselves
very well to Q&amp;A sites,

00:12:19.710 --> 00:12:21.780
because they're
not very granular.

00:12:21.780 --> 00:12:23.960
And we also really
have no experience

00:12:23.960 --> 00:12:26.640
and no legal
framework for allowing

00:12:26.640 --> 00:12:29.390
us to get agile expertise,
for getting answers

00:12:29.390 --> 00:12:30.860
to questions quickly.

00:12:30.860 --> 00:12:34.310
The typical way in which
government gets expertise

00:12:34.310 --> 00:12:37.130
is through something like an
advisory committee, right?

00:12:37.130 --> 00:12:40.260
10 people who sit on
a committee, they meet

00:12:40.260 --> 00:12:43.820
face to face at Whitehall or in
Washington three times a year.

00:12:43.820 --> 00:12:47.130
And they produce an
enormous PDF of 100 pages.

00:12:47.130 --> 00:12:49.680
Before coming here,
I was just meeting

00:12:49.680 --> 00:12:51.550
with an executive
from the NHS who

00:12:51.550 --> 00:12:54.110
is responsible for quality
improvements who was telling me

00:12:54.110 --> 00:12:56.400
about the audits that
the NHS conducts,

00:12:56.400 --> 00:12:59.850
these fabulous data driven
research studies of performance

00:12:59.850 --> 00:13:02.610
by hospitals across the UK.

00:13:02.610 --> 00:13:04.720
But what's the biggest
problem they have?

00:13:04.720 --> 00:13:06.670
It's the 100 page PDF.

00:13:06.670 --> 00:13:11.750
How do you take the 100 page PDF
about hip fractures and stroke,

00:13:11.750 --> 00:13:14.700
chock full of data, and
turn it into 10 things

00:13:14.700 --> 00:13:17.590
that a hospital manager
needs to do or three things

00:13:17.590 --> 00:13:19.330
that the public needs to know?

00:13:19.330 --> 00:13:23.340
We're not very good at
agile in government.

00:13:23.340 --> 00:13:25.480
So the question, and what
I want to sort of spend

00:13:25.480 --> 00:13:27.300
my last few minutes
talking to you about,

00:13:27.300 --> 00:13:30.330
is the strategies we
might use for moving

00:13:30.330 --> 00:13:34.190
from a world of the open
call, crowdsourcing wisely--

00:13:34.190 --> 00:13:36.640
excuse me, crowdsourcing
widely-- hello, anyone out

00:13:36.640 --> 00:13:40.130
there-- to crowdsourcing
a little more widely,

00:13:40.130 --> 00:13:45.150
where we do a small, small
job of curating people

00:13:45.150 --> 00:13:48.290
who are out there who may be
able to supply the expertise

00:13:48.290 --> 00:13:49.390
that we need.

00:13:49.390 --> 00:13:53.580
So imagine that we're facing a
pandemic like the Zika virus.

00:13:53.580 --> 00:13:56.830
And I will interrupt myself
and risk going over my timing

00:13:56.830 --> 00:13:59.650
to tell you a quick
story about this, which

00:13:59.650 --> 00:14:02.810
is I got a call last week by
a multi-national organization

00:14:02.810 --> 00:14:05.930
asking me if I could recommend
a big data expert to help Brazil

00:14:05.930 --> 00:14:10.450
with Zika, to which I just--
I almost fell off my chair.

00:14:10.450 --> 00:14:13.910
You want me to pick
one person, one person,

00:14:13.910 --> 00:14:17.220
who is going to be person
to solve this problem.

00:14:17.220 --> 00:14:20.090
Why would you want one person
in this day and age when

00:14:20.090 --> 00:14:23.260
I could have 100 people, 1,000
people, when I could have

00:14:23.260 --> 00:14:25.489
a big data person, with
a public health person,

00:14:25.489 --> 00:14:27.780
together with somebody who
knows the region, together--

00:14:27.780 --> 00:14:29.600
you get the idea?

00:14:29.600 --> 00:14:33.400
We have the ability to curate
and crowd source expertise

00:14:33.400 --> 00:14:36.680
so that when we need
creative ideas, when

00:14:36.680 --> 00:14:39.790
we need to find the
techies, and the doctors,

00:14:39.790 --> 00:14:43.500
and the taxi drivers, and
the stay-at-home moms,

00:14:43.500 --> 00:14:45.800
and the students, we
should be able to do

00:14:45.800 --> 00:14:47.100
a better job of that.

00:14:47.100 --> 00:14:49.920
We have the data that
does a much better job now

00:14:49.920 --> 00:14:55.910
of telling us what people know
that makes that searchable

00:14:55.910 --> 00:14:59.550
to companies, to NGOs,
and to governments in ways

00:14:59.550 --> 00:15:01.140
that we can make use of.

00:15:01.140 --> 00:15:03.180
So just to give you a
quick, concrete example

00:15:03.180 --> 00:15:05.460
before I launch into
a few developments

00:15:05.460 --> 00:15:08.610
in the public sector-- think
about something like HealthTap.

00:15:08.610 --> 00:15:12.452
I don't know how popular
this is in the UK.

00:15:12.452 --> 00:15:14.160
It's not even that
popular yet in the US.

00:15:14.160 --> 00:15:16.710
But you get the simple
idea that it's a network--

00:15:16.710 --> 00:15:19.590
excuse me-- of
doctors so that when

00:15:19.590 --> 00:15:21.860
I, as the mother
of a small child,

00:15:21.860 --> 00:15:24.790
have-- you know, my kid has
a sniffle, I can go on there

00:15:24.790 --> 00:15:25.630
and find a doctor.

00:15:25.630 --> 00:15:29.240
I can target that expertise and
get the know-how that I need.

00:15:29.240 --> 00:15:31.000
And they're now using
this same network

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:32.870
to connect doctors in
the developed world

00:15:32.870 --> 00:15:35.760
to crises in the
developing world.

00:15:35.760 --> 00:15:37.800
This is because
ultimately, and what

00:15:37.800 --> 00:15:39.850
we could spend a long
time talking about

00:15:39.850 --> 00:15:41.960
is the ways in which
the internet is

00:15:41.960 --> 00:15:46.480
changing how we define expertise
and how we make it searchable.

00:15:46.480 --> 00:15:49.240
If I asked you how many people
in this room are on LinkedIn,

00:15:49.240 --> 00:15:53.186
I'm pretty sure every single
hand would go up, right?

00:15:53.186 --> 00:15:54.560
I'm going to ask
you also-- and I

00:15:54.560 --> 00:15:57.890
am sure Google has a very well
developed knowledge management

00:15:57.890 --> 00:16:00.740
system and HR databases
that will tell you

00:16:00.740 --> 00:16:04.140
all about what peoples' skills
are and make them searchable.

00:16:04.140 --> 00:16:06.540
And we have lots of that
relate to the credentials

00:16:06.540 --> 00:16:08.630
that people have,
but more importantly,

00:16:08.630 --> 00:16:10.275
also to the experience
that people have

00:16:10.275 --> 00:16:11.900
or to the skills that
they have, right?

00:16:11.900 --> 00:16:13.608
If I want to know if
a coder is any good,

00:16:13.608 --> 00:16:14.870
I look at their GitHub repo.

00:16:14.870 --> 00:16:17.720
I don't care what LinkedIn says
about where they got a degree.

00:16:17.720 --> 00:16:20.820
Because 14% of the people at
Google don't have a degree,

00:16:20.820 --> 00:16:21.350
right?

00:16:21.350 --> 00:16:24.074
But it makes them better
coders, not worse coders,

00:16:24.074 --> 00:16:25.990
as long as I know something
about their skills

00:16:25.990 --> 00:16:26.955
and experience.

00:16:26.955 --> 00:16:28.330
Some of you may
have interacted--

00:16:28.330 --> 00:16:30.200
I don't know if--
Panos Ipeirotis, who

00:16:30.200 --> 00:16:33.080
spends his summers
at Google and then

00:16:33.080 --> 00:16:35.660
the rest of the year at
NYU at the Stern School

00:16:35.660 --> 00:16:40.150
has done some amazing work on
quiz.us, a project supported

00:16:40.150 --> 00:16:43.350
by Google, which is,
long story short,

00:16:43.350 --> 00:16:46.000
essentially goes to prove
that people with passion

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:48.120
on a particular
topic-- in other words,

00:16:48.120 --> 00:16:51.340
a patient who has a disease
and spends a lot of time

00:16:51.340 --> 00:16:54.620
on the Web MD, turns out to
know a lot more about a topic

00:16:54.620 --> 00:16:56.050
than a person with a credential.

00:16:56.050 --> 00:16:58.750
And that's something that
he has set out to measure.

00:16:58.750 --> 00:17:03.490
So we're seeing lots of ways
in which we can manifest

00:17:03.490 --> 00:17:06.609
our expertise and lots of ways
in which we can actually make

00:17:06.609 --> 00:17:08.400
it more searchable to people.

00:17:08.400 --> 00:17:10.660
And by that, I'm referring
now to the technologies

00:17:10.660 --> 00:17:12.740
of badges and digital badges.

00:17:12.740 --> 00:17:17.170
So if I go to NYU
and I get a degree,

00:17:17.170 --> 00:17:19.920
I now get a digital badge,
which I can put on LinkedIn,

00:17:19.920 --> 00:17:22.869
or my website, et
cetera, that makes my

00:17:22.869 --> 00:17:24.980
know how more
searchable to people,

00:17:24.980 --> 00:17:28.980
allowing me to showcase
my experience, my skills,

00:17:28.980 --> 00:17:32.150
my interests, my passions from
a variety of different places,

00:17:32.150 --> 00:17:34.380
not just the place
I went to school,

00:17:34.380 --> 00:17:36.410
but many different
indicia of the way

00:17:36.410 --> 00:17:39.590
that I am developing my
know-how and expertise.

00:17:39.590 --> 00:17:42.500
So let me close with
just a couple of examples

00:17:42.500 --> 00:17:44.600
of the ways in
which we're starting

00:17:44.600 --> 00:17:47.460
to see a move towards the
use of this technology

00:17:47.460 --> 00:17:49.900
in the public sector
in the first place

00:17:49.900 --> 00:17:52.450
to better tap into the
know how of civil servants

00:17:52.450 --> 00:17:55.220
and public servants, but then
also to connect government

00:17:55.220 --> 00:17:56.690
to citizens.

00:17:56.690 --> 00:18:00.084
So I'd like-- and if it wasn't
clear from the title already,

00:18:00.084 --> 00:18:02.250
I'd like to think about
this as doing for government

00:18:02.250 --> 00:18:03.620
what we do for dating, right?

00:18:03.620 --> 00:18:05.786
So if you don't like the
toothpaste and the customer

00:18:05.786 --> 00:18:09.260
segmentation example, think
about Tinder as the example.

00:18:09.260 --> 00:18:12.250
Dating websites are really
good at matching people,

00:18:12.250 --> 00:18:16.380
matching us for marriage,
for dating, for a hook up,

00:18:16.380 --> 00:18:18.620
whatever it may be-- it's
to connect people one

00:18:18.620 --> 00:18:20.470
to another based
on their interests.

00:18:20.470 --> 00:18:22.980
If we can take that
same idea and we

00:18:22.980 --> 00:18:25.850
can take the same kinds of
underlying technologies,

00:18:25.850 --> 00:18:28.620
we can do a better job
of actually greasing

00:18:28.620 --> 00:18:30.852
the skids between
how institutions work

00:18:30.852 --> 00:18:31.976
and how they get expertise.

00:18:31.976 --> 00:18:32.770
[RINGTONE]

00:18:32.770 --> 00:18:33.644
Sorry.

00:18:33.644 --> 00:18:38.330
[CHUCKLE] Uh, that's
that other phone.

00:18:38.330 --> 00:18:40.130
Health and Human
Services-- our ministry

00:18:40.130 --> 00:18:41.970
of health in the
United States has

00:18:41.970 --> 00:18:44.730
110,000 people who work there.

00:18:44.730 --> 00:18:47.610
They have the responsibility
for the very hard task

00:18:47.610 --> 00:18:51.690
of deciding on the safety
and efficacy of drugs

00:18:51.690 --> 00:18:54.320
and medical devices
that go out into market.

00:18:54.320 --> 00:18:55.980
They have to get
them out quickly

00:18:55.980 --> 00:18:58.160
if businesses are
to thrive, but not

00:18:58.160 --> 00:19:00.980
so quickly that they risk
killing people with devices

00:19:00.980 --> 00:19:02.180
that are faulty.

00:19:02.180 --> 00:19:03.940
So they've set up now
an expert network,

00:19:03.940 --> 00:19:06.530
the kind of knowledge
management system that's

00:19:06.530 --> 00:19:08.310
common to companies,
but to allow

00:19:08.310 --> 00:19:10.810
them to tap into the
expertise or resources

00:19:10.810 --> 00:19:13.880
that they have across the
department, across the agency,

00:19:13.880 --> 00:19:16.300
something that had never
been able to do before.

00:19:16.300 --> 00:19:18.600
And the hope is that that
will accelerate how they

00:19:18.600 --> 00:19:20.970
get expertise and do their job.

00:19:20.970 --> 00:19:22.780
It's more though than
just about getting

00:19:22.780 --> 00:19:25.310
at credentials and diplomas,
like who has what degree

00:19:25.310 --> 00:19:26.890
or what publications in health?

00:19:26.890 --> 00:19:29.110
It's also about getting at
what that experience is.

00:19:29.110 --> 00:19:33.150
So the World Bank just this year
has put its 27,000 employees

00:19:33.150 --> 00:19:34.392
on an expert network.

00:19:34.392 --> 00:19:35.850
And finding though
that they didn't

00:19:35.850 --> 00:19:38.830
know how to use that to
translate into better

00:19:38.830 --> 00:19:41.340
outcomes for solving
global poverty,

00:19:41.340 --> 00:19:42.932
they also built a help desk.

00:19:42.932 --> 00:19:44.390
So that now what
you do is you say,

00:19:44.390 --> 00:19:46.181
I'm looking for somebody
who has experience

00:19:46.181 --> 00:19:50.170
in setting up a well in
this part of Burkina Faso.

00:19:50.170 --> 00:19:52.570
And the help desk will in
turn use the digital tools

00:19:52.570 --> 00:19:55.340
to help you navigate
knowledge within the Bank

00:19:55.340 --> 00:19:58.260
in order to allow them to
source the expertise that they

00:19:58.260 --> 00:20:01.260
have internally that they
don't even know that they have.

00:20:01.260 --> 00:20:02.740
The mayor's office
in New York City

00:20:02.740 --> 00:20:04.530
does something similar
for finding people

00:20:04.530 --> 00:20:07.700
who have the ability to speak
Albanian, or Serbo-Croation,

00:20:07.700 --> 00:20:10.194
or whatever it may be at
the time that it's needed.

00:20:10.194 --> 00:20:11.610
And we're starting
to see examples

00:20:11.610 --> 00:20:13.410
of this kind of
technology coming

00:20:13.410 --> 00:20:14.810
into public institutions.

00:20:14.810 --> 00:20:17.040
Half the civil service
in Canada is now

00:20:17.040 --> 00:20:19.040
connected on GC Connects.

00:20:19.040 --> 00:20:20.910
But we're just at the beginning.

00:20:20.910 --> 00:20:23.370
And you have calls both
in the United States

00:20:23.370 --> 00:20:26.860
and in Britain, of course, for
using more technology to better

00:20:26.860 --> 00:20:30.470
tap into the human capital that
we have in the civil service.

00:20:30.470 --> 00:20:32.550
I don't have time today
to go into many more

00:20:32.550 --> 00:20:33.400
of these examples.

00:20:33.400 --> 00:20:35.369
I'll just end with one or two.

00:20:35.369 --> 00:20:37.160
But if you are interested
in some of these,

00:20:37.160 --> 00:20:40.310
or know about more, or want
to share more about what's

00:20:40.310 --> 00:20:42.347
going on in the private
sector that people

00:20:42.347 --> 00:20:43.930
in the public sector
could learn from,

00:20:43.930 --> 00:20:46.360
we are trying to collect
some of these case studies

00:20:46.360 --> 00:20:48.580
at a website called
Smarter State.

00:20:48.580 --> 00:20:51.900
So let me just close by talking
about the ways in which we are

00:20:51.900 --> 00:20:55.140
making the transition
from connecting

00:20:55.140 --> 00:20:59.250
civil servants better, creating
better organizational learning

00:20:59.250 --> 00:21:02.900
and better teams in
public institutions,

00:21:02.900 --> 00:21:06.000
to looking at how this affects
our ability for institutions

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:09.220
to change how they
work with citizens.

00:21:09.220 --> 00:21:11.490
There are lots of these
knowledge networks beginning

00:21:11.490 --> 00:21:12.580
to creep up.

00:21:12.580 --> 00:21:15.490
Vivo Web is connecting
over 200,000 academics.

00:21:15.490 --> 00:21:19.220
And Agra Vivo is now creating
the spin-off for people

00:21:19.220 --> 00:21:22.720
with agricultural expertise.

00:21:22.720 --> 00:21:25.590
And we're seeing also
again some movement,

00:21:25.590 --> 00:21:29.670
very early, towards looking
at how do we actually do this,

00:21:29.670 --> 00:21:32.520
going beyond traditional
credentials and research

00:21:32.520 --> 00:21:35.440
networking, you know, going
beyond what Google Scholar can

00:21:35.440 --> 00:21:38.400
do in terms of telling me
what my publications are

00:21:38.400 --> 00:21:40.880
and my citations, to
looking at how we tap

00:21:40.880 --> 00:21:43.000
into the skills of
people in a community

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:45.240
so that we can get
engagement that isn't just

00:21:45.240 --> 00:21:48.310
cerebral and credentialed,
but is also about boots

00:21:48.310 --> 00:21:50.990
on the ground, getting people
to help and participate

00:21:50.990 --> 00:21:51.920
in new ways.

00:21:51.920 --> 00:21:54.360
Podemos, the upstart
political party in Spain,

00:21:54.360 --> 00:21:56.960
has created something
called Banco de Talentos

00:21:56.960 --> 00:22:00.270
to start to inventory the
skills and ability of the people

00:22:00.270 --> 00:22:02.670
in their own movement,
in their own party,

00:22:02.670 --> 00:22:06.460
in the hope that they can better
figure out ways to tap into it.

00:22:06.460 --> 00:22:09.027
So the last example, and
probably the most powerful one,

00:22:09.027 --> 00:22:11.360
and there is-- I've been using
this example for a while,

00:22:11.360 --> 00:22:13.470
because there continues
to be none better.

00:22:13.470 --> 00:22:17.060
But I think it's the
beginning of what's possible.

00:22:17.060 --> 00:22:19.390
That is the ability
again to use technology

00:22:19.390 --> 00:22:23.320
to target a single skill,
in this case, the ability

00:22:23.320 --> 00:22:26.650
to perform CPR and
use a defibrillator.

00:22:26.650 --> 00:22:30.340
So if you were in Mountain
View in California,

00:22:30.340 --> 00:22:32.390
and before PulsePoint
came along,

00:22:32.390 --> 00:22:34.570
and you had a heart
attack, these dots

00:22:34.570 --> 00:22:37.370
represent the police,
and fire, and ambulance

00:22:37.370 --> 00:22:40.150
who would come and save you in
the event you had an accident

00:22:40.150 --> 00:22:41.490
or had a heart attack.

00:22:41.490 --> 00:22:46.370
Come PulsePoint, open
data feeds from 999 or 911

00:22:46.370 --> 00:22:49.110
in the United
States, geolocation

00:22:49.110 --> 00:22:53.760
using my cell phone or any
cell phone, I might add,

00:22:53.760 --> 00:22:58.630
that allows one to know where
I am vis a vis the victim.

00:22:58.630 --> 00:23:01.500
And suddenly my coverage
in terms of first response

00:23:01.500 --> 00:23:03.020
looks like this, right?

00:23:03.020 --> 00:23:06.100
And for every second the victim
of a heart attack-- excuse me,

00:23:06.100 --> 00:23:07.870
every minute the victim
of a heart attack

00:23:07.870 --> 00:23:11.110
gets bystander CPR,
gets aid sooner,

00:23:11.110 --> 00:23:14.040
doubles the chances of their
likelihood of survival.

00:23:14.040 --> 00:23:17.640
1,400 communities now in the
United States use PulsePoint.

00:23:17.640 --> 00:23:19.750
And as of four months
ago, the same service

00:23:19.750 --> 00:23:22.250
called GoodSAM, a
service of the London Air

00:23:22.250 --> 00:23:24.580
Ambulance out of St.
Mary's Hospital here,

00:23:24.580 --> 00:23:26.350
provides the same
thing in London.

00:23:26.350 --> 00:23:28.520
So if there's no other
message that you take away

00:23:28.520 --> 00:23:31.370
from me today, it's
please sign up for this.

00:23:31.370 --> 00:23:33.470
Please sign up and save a life.

00:23:33.470 --> 00:23:37.840
Because there is a way now
for us to use technology

00:23:37.840 --> 00:23:41.290
to target people's ability
and willingness to serve,

00:23:41.290 --> 00:23:44.290
the supply of expertise
with the demand for it,

00:23:44.290 --> 00:23:46.340
namely people who
can perform CPR,

00:23:46.340 --> 00:23:49.430
who can use a defibrillator,
with a very real outcome,

00:23:49.430 --> 00:23:51.222
which is to save a life.

00:23:51.222 --> 00:23:52.680
So we should talk
in our discussion

00:23:52.680 --> 00:23:54.430
about how do we get
from here to there?

00:23:54.430 --> 00:23:57.380
There's a lot that we have to
do if we're to actually enable

00:23:57.380 --> 00:23:59.820
these kinds of platforms,
if we're actually

00:23:59.820 --> 00:24:01.770
to enable these
kinds of processes.

00:24:01.770 --> 00:24:04.820
We've got to want to do
it, first and foremost.

00:24:04.820 --> 00:24:07.610
And we have to overcome
a lot of legal hurdles.

00:24:07.610 --> 00:24:10.910
I won't get into the minutiae
of US law or British law.

00:24:10.910 --> 00:24:12.790
But suffice it to
say, we don't have

00:24:12.790 --> 00:24:16.070
the legal frameworks that allow
us to do this very well yet.

00:24:16.070 --> 00:24:19.770
We have to have the digital
badges and credentialing

00:24:19.770 --> 00:24:23.510
systems that allow us
to actually do a better

00:24:23.510 --> 00:24:25.060
job of finding expertise.

00:24:25.060 --> 00:24:26.660
So I've given you a
bunch of examples,

00:24:26.660 --> 00:24:29.580
but we're just at the beginning
of actually making searchable

00:24:29.580 --> 00:24:30.862
what people know.

00:24:30.862 --> 00:24:32.320
And companies like
Google have been

00:24:32.320 --> 00:24:35.160
at the forefront, along with
foundations like Lumina, trying

00:24:35.160 --> 00:24:39.720
to sponsor the creation of more
liquid badging systems, skill

00:24:39.720 --> 00:24:42.290
based systems, digital
credentialing systems

00:24:42.290 --> 00:24:44.080
so we can do that
kind of matching.

00:24:44.080 --> 00:24:48.630
LinkedIn is involved in this
here in Manchester, et cetera.

00:24:48.630 --> 00:24:49.790
So right?

00:24:49.790 --> 00:24:52.750
This is your HR guy.

00:24:52.750 --> 00:24:54.790
We don't care about
degrees anymore.

00:24:54.790 --> 00:24:57.090
That means we need the
tools to better find out

00:24:57.090 --> 00:24:59.350
what skills people have
and what they know.

00:24:59.350 --> 00:25:01.500
Those same kinds
of platforms that

00:25:01.500 --> 00:25:03.757
are getting developed
for industry,

00:25:03.757 --> 00:25:05.590
that are getting developed
to better connect

00:25:05.590 --> 00:25:08.120
job seekers to
jobs, can also help

00:25:08.120 --> 00:25:10.750
us now to connect people
to opportunities to serve

00:25:10.750 --> 00:25:13.720
and to govern better as we
build more of these credentials,

00:25:13.720 --> 00:25:15.890
as we build more
of these networks,

00:25:15.890 --> 00:25:18.530
and as we try more
to see what works.

00:25:18.530 --> 00:25:21.100
So finally, Will, I don't
have all the answers.

00:25:21.100 --> 00:25:22.450
I don't know what works.

00:25:22.450 --> 00:25:24.780
I know that we need to do
a bunch of experiments.

00:25:24.780 --> 00:25:27.600
We need to compare, you
know, whether the thing

00:25:27.600 --> 00:25:29.590
that the Health and
Human Services is doing

00:25:29.590 --> 00:25:32.420
to find experts to
examine medical devices

00:25:32.420 --> 00:25:36.180
by targeted expertise works
better than the system

00:25:36.180 --> 00:25:38.470
that the Environmental
Protection Agency is putting

00:25:38.470 --> 00:25:41.080
in place to post projects
and say, hey, anyone

00:25:41.080 --> 00:25:44.460
out there with these
skills within the agency--

00:25:44.460 --> 00:25:46.170
does that self-selection
work better?

00:25:46.170 --> 00:25:48.740
Does the targeting work better?

00:25:48.740 --> 00:25:50.760
We're going to find
out as we do it more.

00:25:50.760 --> 00:25:53.340
We're going to find out
as more people volunteer

00:25:53.340 --> 00:25:56.310
to make themselves more
findable and more searchable

00:25:56.310 --> 00:25:59.660
so that we can solve the
problems that we face.

00:25:59.660 --> 00:26:02.716
Let me close by saying,
we have to do this.

00:26:02.716 --> 00:26:04.250
This is not a nice-to-have.

00:26:04.250 --> 00:26:07.140
This is not about the, oh,
democratic participation

00:26:07.140 --> 00:26:09.920
would be nice, because
it builds legitimacy.

00:26:09.920 --> 00:26:11.580
That's a good thing, right?

00:26:11.580 --> 00:26:13.350
And if you are a
democratic theorist,

00:26:13.350 --> 00:26:16.230
or a participatory
democrat, or just a citizen,

00:26:16.230 --> 00:26:18.350
you really care
about the legitimacy

00:26:18.350 --> 00:26:20.550
that comes from
citizen participation.

00:26:20.550 --> 00:26:22.990
Maybe you had to read
your Habermas in school.

00:26:22.990 --> 00:26:27.270
And you know how important
legitimacy building can be.

00:26:27.270 --> 00:26:30.380
But I would argue it
is a false dichotomy

00:26:30.380 --> 00:26:34.520
to suggest that participation
is simply about legitimacy,

00:26:34.520 --> 00:26:36.490
and then the
bureaucrats over here,

00:26:36.490 --> 00:26:38.500
the people behind
the closed doors,

00:26:38.500 --> 00:26:40.520
they're the ones who
get the real work done.

00:26:40.520 --> 00:26:42.420
And when you want to
effective outcomes,

00:26:42.420 --> 00:26:44.600
you have to do that
behind closed doors.

00:26:44.600 --> 00:26:46.180
We know better than that today.

00:26:46.180 --> 00:26:48.290
We know that we
have to produce--

00:26:48.290 --> 00:26:50.840
if we wanted innovation, we
have to produce it openly.

00:26:50.840 --> 00:26:53.450
And if we want to deal with the
challenges of global warming,

00:26:53.450 --> 00:26:57.330
and immigration, and Europe,
and all these hard problems

00:26:57.330 --> 00:26:59.330
that we deal with in
the political realm,

00:26:59.330 --> 00:27:02.120
we have to have a machinery of
government that does a better

00:27:02.120 --> 00:27:04.640
job at stewarding
those conversations

00:27:04.640 --> 00:27:06.450
and of bringing
in that expertise.

00:27:06.450 --> 00:27:08.870
Credentialed know-how,
boots on the ground,

00:27:08.870 --> 00:27:10.690
and people doing
tasks-- either way,

00:27:10.690 --> 00:27:13.010
tech will help us over
the next five years

00:27:13.010 --> 00:27:16.020
to build participation.gov,
not just data.gov.

00:27:16.020 --> 00:27:17.060
So thank you very much.

