this is about creating many,
many more forms of engagement,

00:34:36.320 --> 00:34:38.360
some of which may be
very small and granular,

00:34:38.360 --> 00:34:41.230
10 minutes of your
time, and some of which

00:34:41.230 --> 00:34:45.770
may be a much more significant
commitment backed by funding,

00:34:45.770 --> 00:34:47.330
or a prize, et cetera.

00:34:47.330 --> 00:34:52.980
So we just need more variety
in the opportunities.

00:34:52.980 --> 00:34:55.290
So there's a hand all
the way in the back.

00:34:55.290 --> 00:34:56.639
I don't know if we have to-- oh.

00:34:56.639 --> 00:34:57.940
Thank you, mic runner.

00:35:03.664 --> 00:35:04.630
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:35:04.630 --> 00:35:06.610
So I'm, I guess, a
computer scientist

00:35:06.610 --> 00:35:08.380
is how I describe myself.

00:35:08.380 --> 00:35:10.100
I'm not sure, by
the way, I accept

00:35:10.100 --> 00:35:12.625
the thesis that the tech
industry is that successful

00:35:12.625 --> 00:35:14.190
or a model for government.

00:35:14.190 --> 00:35:16.490
But even supposing I did,
what about responsibility?

00:35:16.490 --> 00:35:18.570
One of the key things
I want from government

00:35:18.570 --> 00:35:20.582
and which the tech
industry is frequently

00:35:20.582 --> 00:35:22.665
accused of not having is
a sense of responsibility

00:35:22.665 --> 00:35:26.190
and mechanisms of
responsibility.

00:35:26.190 --> 00:35:27.930
How do you see
that being grafted

00:35:27.930 --> 00:35:30.290
on these quite open
platforms where, you know,

00:35:30.290 --> 00:35:33.270
anyone can swarm in and write
something on Stack Overflow,

00:35:33.270 --> 00:35:34.700
and maybe it doesn't work.

00:35:34.700 --> 00:35:36.356
Or maybe it's self-serving.

00:35:36.356 --> 00:35:38.480
BETH NOVECK: So let me say
that in the first place,

00:35:38.480 --> 00:35:44.370
I am not suggesting--
well, I want

00:35:44.370 --> 00:35:47.150
to-- let me-- there
are ways in which

00:35:47.150 --> 00:35:52.090
and places in which we have
seen radical devolution of power

00:35:52.090 --> 00:35:55.740
and authority downward to
citizens and much more bottom

00:35:55.740 --> 00:35:56.940
up processes.

00:35:56.940 --> 00:35:59.770
So take, for example,
participatory budgeting,

00:35:59.770 --> 00:36:03.710
where small portions
of municipal budgets

00:36:03.710 --> 00:36:06.430
in about 1,500 different
cities around the world

00:36:06.430 --> 00:36:08.730
are handed to a
group of citizens,

00:36:08.730 --> 00:36:11.380
in a fully transparent
deliberative process,

00:36:11.380 --> 00:36:14.770
to decide how to spend
instead of the city

00:36:14.770 --> 00:36:16.920
councilmen and politicians
who would usually

00:36:16.920 --> 00:36:18.510
make that decision.

00:36:18.510 --> 00:36:21.650
I am thinking here,
though, about making a move

00:36:21.650 --> 00:36:24.820
towards more open
forms of engagement,

00:36:24.820 --> 00:36:27.330
not necessarily by
abdicating or getting

00:36:27.330 --> 00:36:29.385
rid of government in this case.

00:36:29.385 --> 00:36:31.510
So in the Peer to Patent
project that we worked on,

00:36:31.510 --> 00:36:33.470
we didn't get rid of
the patent examiner.

00:36:33.470 --> 00:36:35.720
There was a very important
role for that person

00:36:35.720 --> 00:36:41.570
to play as essentially the
arbiter of the legal standards.

00:36:41.570 --> 00:36:44.370
Because a patent examiner--
patent examination

00:36:44.370 --> 00:36:47.490
involves two pieces, a lot of
technical know-how and then

00:36:47.490 --> 00:36:50.070
the ability to apply a legal
standard about the relevance

00:36:50.070 --> 00:36:53.090
of that technical know-how to
the decision about the patent.

00:36:53.090 --> 00:36:54.950
There was an ultimate
decision-maker

00:36:54.950 --> 00:36:56.590
who remained at
the center and who

00:36:56.590 --> 00:36:58.700
was the arbiter, essentially,
of the information

00:36:58.700 --> 00:36:59.830
that was coming in.

00:36:59.830 --> 00:37:02.970
So in many cases, this
is about maintaining

00:37:02.970 --> 00:37:05.720
those pathways of
decision making and power

00:37:05.720 --> 00:37:10.000
but doing a better job of
bringing evidence, and data,

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:13.190
and know-how into how
those decisions get made.

00:37:13.190 --> 00:37:16.170
One more kind of answer
by way of analogy-- I

00:37:16.170 --> 00:37:18.460
had a guy who worked
for me last year.

00:37:18.460 --> 00:37:21.420
He was responsible for small
business policy in the White

00:37:21.420 --> 00:37:23.380
House before he
came to work for me.

00:37:23.380 --> 00:37:27.860
He was 24 years old when he
worked for me and 22 years old

00:37:27.860 --> 00:37:29.280
when he worked in
the White House.

00:37:29.280 --> 00:37:31.310
He had never owned
a small business.

00:37:31.310 --> 00:37:32.580
Now he was very smart.

00:37:32.580 --> 00:37:36.560
And he had an Ivy League
degree or two by that point.

00:37:36.560 --> 00:37:39.540
But he had no know-how
and no experience and had,

00:37:39.540 --> 00:37:41.360
you know, a couple
of days to formulate

00:37:41.360 --> 00:37:43.280
what would be a national
policy affecting

00:37:43.280 --> 00:37:44.830
large numbers of people.

00:37:44.830 --> 00:37:46.914
That's how decision making
gets done today, right?

00:37:46.914 --> 00:37:48.871
I don't know how many
people have seen-- what's

00:37:48.871 --> 00:37:50.770
that great movie about--
with Peter Capaldi

00:37:50.770 --> 00:37:52.844
about the British government?

00:37:52.844 --> 00:37:54.010
AUDIENCE: "The Thick of It."

00:37:54.010 --> 00:37:54.400
BETH NOVECK: What?

00:37:54.400 --> 00:37:55.400
AUDIENCE: "The Thick of It."

00:37:55.400 --> 00:37:56.530
BETH NOVECK: "In the Thick
of It--" "The Thick of It"

00:37:56.530 --> 00:37:57.320
was the TV show.

00:37:57.320 --> 00:37:59.029
The movie-- "In the
Loop," "In the Loop."

00:37:59.029 --> 00:38:01.569
So I don't know if you remember
the scene where Peter Capaldi

00:38:01.569 --> 00:38:02.830
walks into the White House.

00:38:02.830 --> 00:38:05.380
And this, like,
12-year-old kid comes in.

00:38:05.380 --> 00:38:06.860
And he orders coffee from him.

00:38:06.860 --> 00:38:09.760
And he explains, no, no, no, he
is the senior policy adviser.

00:38:09.760 --> 00:38:12.320
That's very typical to
how government gets made.

00:38:12.320 --> 00:38:13.540
Here they call them the SPAD.

00:38:13.540 --> 00:38:15.750
We call them the
special assistant.

00:38:15.750 --> 00:38:18.320
Whether you're 22
or 52, the ability

00:38:18.320 --> 00:38:20.350
to have all the
knowledge that you

00:38:20.350 --> 00:38:23.430
need to make the decisions
which government does

00:38:23.430 --> 00:38:25.320
is very, very limited.

00:38:25.320 --> 00:38:27.190
So the point is,
how do we open up

00:38:27.190 --> 00:38:30.320
the decision making processes,
bring in more information,

00:38:30.320 --> 00:38:34.640
and still maintain the pathways
of accountability that we have,

00:38:34.640 --> 00:38:38.210
that government can be
quite good at doing?

00:38:38.210 --> 00:38:41.590
So sorry, that's a long,
perhaps not-- I don't know.

00:38:41.590 --> 00:38:43.739
You're looking quite skeptical.

00:38:43.739 --> 00:38:44.780
You're looking skeptical.

00:38:44.780 --> 00:38:47.071
And then what you should be
saying to me is, well then,

00:38:47.071 --> 00:38:49.560
but doesn't that still-- if
you keep those same decision

00:38:49.560 --> 00:38:51.790
making pathways, then
can't I simply ignore

00:38:51.790 --> 00:38:54.700
all the evidence and just
make whatever decision I want?

00:38:54.700 --> 00:38:56.870
Well, that's the problem
of politics, right?

00:38:56.870 --> 00:38:59.900
But at least if we
have a paper trail,

00:38:59.900 --> 00:39:02.420
at least if we have a
record, at least if we have

00:39:02.420 --> 00:39:05.210
the evidence out there,
and the data available,

00:39:05.210 --> 00:39:07.530
and the conflicting
opinions, you

00:39:07.530 --> 00:39:10.130
will have to do a better job
of justifying your desire

00:39:10.130 --> 00:39:13.460
to make a decision that flies
in the face of that evidence.

00:39:13.460 --> 00:39:17.400
Right now, the 22-year-olds get
to make those decisions without

00:39:17.400 --> 00:39:18.870
the benefit of that, so--

00:39:29.042 --> 00:39:31.500
AUDIENCE: I was then imagining
the 22-year-old is sat there

00:39:31.500 --> 00:39:34.800
with 10,000 submissions from
angry members of the public.

00:39:34.800 --> 00:39:38.920
I'm wondering how we're
going to-- perhaps

00:39:38.920 --> 00:39:41.400
we need more people
on the government side

00:39:41.400 --> 00:39:44.531
in order to be able to deal
with this participatory decision

00:39:44.531 --> 00:39:45.030
making.

00:39:46.984 --> 00:39:48.400
BETH NOVECK: So
that's why we have

00:39:48.400 --> 00:39:49.960
to move away from two things.

00:39:49.960 --> 00:39:53.490
One is asking people how they
feel and the open call, right?

00:39:53.490 --> 00:39:56.030
If I ask you how you
feel about small business

00:39:56.030 --> 00:39:58.500
policy in the
United States, what

00:39:58.500 --> 00:39:59.730
are you going to say to me?

00:39:59.730 --> 00:40:02.063
Well, you're not going to say
anything, because you have

00:40:02.063 --> 00:40:03.279
a job to do, and you're busy.

00:40:03.279 --> 00:40:04.820
But the person I'm
going to hear from

00:40:04.820 --> 00:40:06.540
is the person who
is nothing else

00:40:06.540 --> 00:40:11.330
to do besides tell you what
a crap job you're doing,

00:40:11.330 --> 00:40:11.950
essentially.

00:40:11.950 --> 00:40:15.480
So I am the person who
has the misfortune,

00:40:15.480 --> 00:40:18.740
if you want to call it that,
of coming into government

00:40:18.740 --> 00:40:22.350
on the first days of the
Obama administration in 2008

00:40:22.350 --> 00:40:26.700
and being so inclined, said,
we should have a WordPress blog

00:40:26.700 --> 00:40:27.558
with comments.

00:40:27.558 --> 00:40:30.366
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:31.310 --> 00:40:33.220
Yeah.

00:40:33.220 --> 00:40:35.900
Well, I got my picture
in the "New York Times,"

00:40:35.900 --> 00:40:37.980
not for the reason
that you would want to.

00:40:37.980 --> 00:40:40.220
And I will just tell you
that the next day, they

00:40:40.220 --> 00:40:42.570
put a sign up on my door--
when I came into work,

00:40:42.570 --> 00:40:47.750
the sign on my door said
"Area 51, Director of--"

00:40:47.750 --> 00:40:50.460
what was it-- "Director
of Intergalactic Affairs."

00:40:50.460 --> 00:40:53.110
Because I was getting so
many nut jobs telling me

00:40:53.110 --> 00:40:56.120
about Martians landing,
and President Obama's birth

00:40:56.120 --> 00:40:57.890
certificate, and the
birth certificate

00:40:57.890 --> 00:41:00.025
that was on Mars
with the Martians.

00:41:00.025 --> 00:41:01.635
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:01.635 --> 00:41:04.010
And no, they were not all from
Donald Trump at that time.

00:41:04.010 --> 00:41:08.990
But the point is, if you just
do the open comment process,

00:41:08.990 --> 00:41:10.610
that is what you will get.

00:41:10.610 --> 00:41:12.590
You will not get
info that's helpful.

00:41:12.590 --> 00:41:15.070
You'll get "Deport Justin
Bieber Back to Canada."

00:41:15.070 --> 00:41:17.240
And though you may think
that is an important area

00:41:17.240 --> 00:41:19.290
of national policy
making, I would

00:41:19.290 --> 00:41:22.770
like to think that that
naked suggestion by itself

00:41:22.770 --> 00:41:24.750
doesn't help us to
make better decisions.

00:41:24.750 --> 00:41:28.340
If you want me to deport
Justin Bieber back to Canada,

00:41:28.340 --> 00:41:30.310
then you should tell
me how to do it, right?

00:41:30.310 --> 00:41:35.120
We need better expertise about
how to implement policy, not

00:41:35.120 --> 00:41:36.660
just how to make that policy.

00:41:36.660 --> 00:41:40.500
So the point is that
everywhere along the arc of how

00:41:40.500 --> 00:41:42.970
a service gets delivered
or a problem gets

00:41:42.970 --> 00:41:45.410
solved, starting
from just identifying

00:41:45.410 --> 00:41:48.990
with the problems are, to coming
up with possible solutions

00:41:48.990 --> 00:41:52.150
to those problems,
to deciding how

00:41:52.150 --> 00:41:54.330
to implement those
solutions, those are

00:41:54.330 --> 00:41:56.210
all opportunities for input.

00:41:56.210 --> 00:41:57.850
But we know better.

00:41:57.850 --> 00:42:00.750
And this is where I mean
about learning a bit from how

00:42:00.750 --> 00:42:02.260
other people have done this.

00:42:02.260 --> 00:42:04.110
It's not because I
think we should run--

00:42:04.110 --> 00:42:06.880
unlike some people, I don't
think we should turn Washington

00:42:06.880 --> 00:42:08.280
into Silicon Valley.

00:42:08.280 --> 00:42:10.147
There are many people
who believe that.

00:42:10.147 --> 00:42:11.855
But because we can do
a little bit better

00:42:11.855 --> 00:42:14.737
a job of structuring how
we ask people, right?

00:42:14.737 --> 00:42:16.570
Ask people a hard
question, and you will get

00:42:16.570 --> 00:42:20.280
a hard answer is the wisdom.

00:42:20.280 --> 00:42:21.860
Ask people to do
the heavy lifting.

00:42:21.860 --> 00:42:24.350
Don't just tell me to deport
Justin Bieber back to Canada.

00:42:24.350 --> 00:42:26.370
Don't just tell me to
build a Death Star.

00:42:26.370 --> 00:42:27.990
Give me the blueprints,
and then I'll

00:42:27.990 --> 00:42:29.710
build you a Death Star, right?

00:42:29.710 --> 00:42:31.830
Otherwise you get
1,000 suggestions

00:42:31.830 --> 00:42:34.770
like this and no more hours
in the day in which to do it.

00:42:34.770 --> 00:42:36.220
But if you give
me the blueprints,

00:42:36.220 --> 00:42:40.065
I'm much more likely-- and a
budget-- I'm much more likely--

00:42:40.065 --> 00:42:40.660
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:40.660 --> 00:42:42.982
--and the money,
then I'm much more

00:42:42.982 --> 00:42:44.440
likely to build
you the Death Star.

00:42:44.440 --> 00:42:46.490
So I'm being half facetious.

00:42:46.490 --> 00:42:48.910
So let me-- I know you
want to-- there's rebuttal

00:42:48.910 --> 00:42:50.190
coming in the back.

00:42:50.190 --> 00:42:52.820
But let me see if there's
any more new commenters

00:42:52.820 --> 00:42:54.274
or questions before we--

00:42:54.274 --> 00:42:55.690
AUDIENCE: Well, I
have a question.

00:42:55.690 --> 00:42:57.689
BETH NOVECK: --I let him
have at me in a second.

00:42:57.689 --> 00:42:58.990
Because--

00:42:58.990 --> 00:43:01.710
AUDIENCE: Big companies and big
charities are, by the nature,

00:43:01.710 --> 00:43:02.670
international.

00:43:02.670 --> 00:43:07.515
Governments and their users'
data, their citizens' data

00:43:07.515 --> 00:43:08.700
have borders.

00:43:08.700 --> 00:43:12.520
What's being done to bridge
the gap, and what can be done?

00:43:12.520 --> 00:43:15.900
BETH NOVECK: So I think--
so favorite example here,

00:43:15.900 --> 00:43:17.750
I was trying to
remember the name.

00:43:17.750 --> 00:43:21.140
So it's a little town
in Texas, Manor, Texas.

00:43:21.140 --> 00:43:23.800
It's a suburb of-- when I tell
you it's a suburb of Austin,

00:43:23.800 --> 00:43:26.890
it sounds less glamor--
less cowboy like.

00:43:26.890 --> 00:43:28.910
But just take my word for it.

00:43:28.910 --> 00:43:30.670
This is a very
small town in Texas.

00:43:30.670 --> 00:43:31.410
I've been there.

00:43:31.410 --> 00:43:34.030
It has about 5,000
people who live there.

00:43:34.030 --> 00:43:37.180
5,000 people-- that's not
a lot of room for creating

00:43:37.180 --> 00:43:38.350
a public service, right?

00:43:38.350 --> 00:43:41.700
So you had the guy who
became the deputy mayor.

00:43:41.700 --> 00:43:43.320
He was about 24 years old.

00:43:43.320 --> 00:43:45.380
He was also the CFO.

00:43:45.380 --> 00:43:47.980
He was also this, and also
that, and also the other thing.

00:43:47.980 --> 00:43:50.720
And he had some computer
savvy, whether it was

00:43:50.720 --> 00:43:52.830
formal training or otherwise.

00:43:52.830 --> 00:43:55.880
And so he had the good idea
that the best way to tackle

00:43:55.880 --> 00:43:59.360
Manor's challenges, of which
there were many in a small town

00:43:59.360 --> 00:44:02.020
with a high rate
of joblessness, was

00:44:02.020 --> 00:44:06.130
to use a challenge platform
to look for good ideas

00:44:06.130 --> 00:44:08.200
to solve particular problems.

00:44:08.200 --> 00:44:12.160
And knowing that prizes often
create an incentive for people

00:44:12.160 --> 00:44:14.980
to participate,
prizes were things

00:44:14.980 --> 00:44:18.280
like if you solved problem
x in the school system,

00:44:18.280 --> 00:44:20.107
you would win a cowboy hat.

00:44:20.107 --> 00:44:21.690
If you dealt with
problem y, you would

00:44:21.690 --> 00:44:23.940
get to ride along with
the Sheriff for a day--

00:44:23.940 --> 00:44:25.180
and other things like that.

00:44:25.180 --> 00:44:26.750
What happens?

00:44:26.750 --> 00:44:29.242
He starts getting great
ideas for how to govern

00:44:29.242 --> 00:44:30.200
better and differently.

00:44:30.200 --> 00:44:31.741
But the ideas are
coming from Europe.

00:44:31.741 --> 00:44:33.060
They're coming from China.

00:44:33.060 --> 00:44:34.630
They're not coming from Texas.

00:44:34.630 --> 00:44:36.300
And quite literally,
he said to me--

00:44:36.300 --> 00:44:38.680
and I think we published
this somewhere-- the hardest

00:44:38.680 --> 00:44:42.172
problem I had was how to
mail a cowboy hat to Beijing.

00:44:42.172 --> 00:44:44.100
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:44.100 --> 00:44:46.770
So I think you hit on
a very important point

00:44:46.770 --> 00:44:50.620
that I had wanted to mention--
is that ultimately when

00:44:50.620 --> 00:44:54.450
we start to recognize and
take seriously the distributed

00:44:54.450 --> 00:44:57.860
expertise that we have and
to look at ways that we can

00:44:57.860 --> 00:45:00.640
connect it better to
how institutions work,

00:45:00.640 --> 00:45:03.130
we quickly realized that
citizens, number one,

00:45:03.130 --> 00:45:04.040
are smart.

00:45:04.040 --> 00:45:07.720
They can do more than just
vote once every year or once

00:45:07.720 --> 00:45:10.580
every four years-- and
also that citizenship

00:45:10.580 --> 00:45:12.190
is not geographic, right?

00:45:12.190 --> 00:45:15.890
It does not need to be
limited to where you live.

00:45:15.890 --> 00:45:18.760
If in fact your
expertise, your passion,

00:45:18.760 --> 00:45:23.850
your know-how may be
around climate change,

00:45:23.850 --> 00:45:28.090
or maybe it's around
dementia, the idea

00:45:28.090 --> 00:45:31.000
that you might become part
of a global network of people

00:45:31.000 --> 00:45:32.750
working on the
problem of dementia,

00:45:32.750 --> 00:45:37.270
or diabetes, or climate change--
we can create the mechanisms

00:45:37.270 --> 00:45:39.620
that I think allow us
to channel expertise

00:45:39.620 --> 00:45:42.760
wherever it may belong
and wherever the need is.

00:45:42.760 --> 00:45:46.940
So just to give you another
analogous example, talking

00:45:46.940 --> 00:45:49.980
to the doctor today
about the 100 page PDFs.

00:45:49.980 --> 00:45:51.740
I said, so what
happens when you get

00:45:51.740 --> 00:45:55.570
that 100 page PDF with
all the data about stroke

00:45:55.570 --> 00:45:57.530
across UK hospitals,
and you have

00:45:57.530 --> 00:46:00.380
to turn that into a
set of recommendations

00:46:00.380 --> 00:46:02.290
